## Pushing updates from a REST route

The real power of WebSockets in a backend service is combining them with your existing REST endpoints. When someone creates a todo via POST, everyone watching the dashboard sees it instantly without polling.

Because `manager` is a module-level object, any route in your app can call `manager.broadcast`:

```python
@app.post('/todos', status_code=201)
async def create_todo(text: str):
    # Save to database...
    new_todo = {'id': 1, 'text': text, 'done': False}

    # Notify all connected clients immediately
    await manager.broadcast(
        json.dumps({'event': 'todo_created', 'todo': new_todo})
    )
    return new_todo
```

The broadcast message is a JSON string with an `event` field. The frontend checks `event` and decides what to do - add a row to the table, increment a counter, play a sound.

### Why JSON strings here

`broadcast` sends to all connections. `send_json` exists on individual WebSocket objects but not on a list. The simplest approach is to serialize to a JSON string yourself with `json.dumps()` and use `send_text` to broadcast it. Each client calls `JSON.parse(event.data)` to decode it.

### On the frontend

```javascript
const ws = new WebSocket('ws://localhost:8000/ws');
ws.onmessage = (event) => {
    const data = JSON.parse(event.data);
    if (data.event === 'todo_created') {
        // add the new todo to the page
        console.log('New todo:', data.todo.text);
    }
};
```

Add a `POST /todos` route that saves the todo and broadcasts a `todo_created` event to all connected clients.

