## Pushing live stats to a dashboard

A dashboard that refreshes itself is one of the most common real-world uses of WebSockets. Instead of the frontend polling `GET /stats` every few seconds, the backend pushes updated numbers every time something changes.

Extend the create and complete routes to broadcast dashboard stats after every change:

```python
import sqlite3

def get_stats() -> dict:
    conn = sqlite3.connect('todos.db')
    row = conn.execute(
        'SELECT COUNT(*) as total, SUM(done) as completed FROM todos'
    ).fetchone()
    conn.close()
    return {
        'total': row[0],
        'completed': row[1] or 0,
        'pending': (row[0] or 0) - (row[1] or 0)
    }

@app.post('/todos', status_code=201)
async def create_todo(text: str):
    # save to DB...
    stats = get_stats()
    await manager.broadcast(
        json.dumps({'event': 'stats_updated', 'stats': stats})
    )
    return {'text': text}

@app.post('/todos/{todo_id}/complete')
async def complete_todo(todo_id: int):
    # update DB...
    stats = get_stats()
    await manager.broadcast(
        json.dumps({'event': 'stats_updated', 'stats': stats})
    )
    return {'completed': True}
```

On the frontend, every time a `stats_updated` event arrives, the dashboard numbers update:

```javascript
ws.onmessage = (event) => {
    const data = JSON.parse(event.data);
    if (data.event === 'stats_updated') {
        document.getElementById('total').textContent = data.stats.total;
        document.getElementById('pending').textContent = data.stats.pending;
        document.getElementById('completed').textContent = data.stats.completed;
    }
};
```

This is the pattern behind every live dashboard you have ever seen - a Stripe revenue counter, a support ticket queue, an analytics screen. The server pushes a small JSON payload whenever state changes, and the frontend just swaps out the numbers.

